    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.03107.001.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="typescript"/>S. S. McCLURE, <lb/>TRIBUNE
                        BUILDING, <lb/>NEW YORK, N. Y.</name>
                    <name type="place"><hi rend="smallcaps">Cable Address, <lb/>"Aiddecamp, New
                            York."</hi></name>
                    <date when="1889-12-03"><handShift rend="typescript"/>Dec. 3, 1889.</date>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="typescript"/>Walt Whitman, Esq.,</name>
                </dateline>
                <salute><handShift rend="typescript"/>Dear Sir:</salute>
            </opener>
            <p><handShift rend="typescript"/>Bishop Potter<ptr target="loc.03107_n1"/> suggests that a short letter giving your ideas how
                best "To lift, how little howsoe'er, the hearts of toilers struggling here," would
                perhaps be a better idea than the one suggested in my previous letter. I should like
                to hear from you in response to either of these questions. A letter of one hundred
                words would perhaps be sufficiently long for this purpose.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute><handShift rend="typescript"/>Very truly yours,</salute>
                <signed><handShift rend="manuscript"/>S. S. McClure</signed>
            </closer>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.03107.002.jpg" type="verso"/>
        </body>
    </text>
